    <h1>- Mouthpiece -</h1>

    <h2>Conception and Inspiration</h2>
    
    <p>My background is, first and foremost, being a composer of contemporary concert music. Music which is meant to be listened to in-concert, 
        usually in a concert hall, performed by live musicians. There is an inherent power dynamic which must be navigated by anyone in this field. 
        As a composer, at least in the most traditional sense of the word, you are writing a piece of music, for which you expect musicians to read, 
        practice, and perform. The composer (again, traditional sense) does not create a single sound which the audience hears. Like the coach of a 
        football team, the composer often gets much credit despite not taking a single metaphorical tackle.</p>

    <p>So I wanted to explore this idea of leeching off of someone’s medium. As a composer, I leech off of instrumentalists and performers, so how 
        could I preserve this idea, this commentary? I figured, what if this parasitic relationship was at the forefront, where the audience could see 
        it happening right in front of their eyes. That was the fundamental idea behind Mouthpiece. A technically simple sonic manipulation device, 
        designed not to create sound on its own, but become the mouthpiece through which others’ sound is appropriated.</p>

    <p>A glove-based system seemed most intuitive to me, from a pure expression and theatrical perspective. There is of course a lot of precedent as 
        well, see <a href="https://mimugloves.com/" target="_blank">Imogen Heap</a> for the biggest inspiration. But honestly, the project didn’t really 
        have any specific project or system in mind, just the aforementioned artistic goal.</p>

